    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "I haven't had time to review but I think I may be -1 on this. If I have\nchanges in submodules that are not committed (or worse, committed but not\ncommitted at top-level), this will either cause setup to fail or silently\nrevert changes.\n\nOn Friday, May 3, 2013, Min RK wrote:\n\n> previously, submodule update would only fire if the submodule dir did not\n> exist. Now, it will try to fire on every setup.py command (when run from a\n> repo), and warn if it fails.\n> \n> Should be a bit less likely to have 'wtf?' moments when the submodule is\n> \n> ## out of date.\n> \n> You can merge this Pull Request by running\n> \n>   git pull https://github.com/minrk/ipython forcefulsubmodule\n> \n> Or view, comment on, or merge it at:\n> \n>   https://github.com/ipython/ipython/pull/3274\n> Commit Summary\n> - be a bit more forceful when checking / updating submodules\n> \n> File Changes\n> - _M_ ipython.pyhttps://github.com/ipython/ipython/pull/3274/files#diff-0(6)\n> - _M_ setup.pyhttps://github.com/ipython/ipython/pull/3274/files#diff-1(8)\n> - _M_ setupbase.pyhttps://github.com/ipython/ipython/pull/3274/files#diff-2(26)\n> \n> Patch Links:\n> - https://github.com/ipython/ipython/pull/3274.patch\n> - https://github.com/ipython/ipython/pull/3274.diff\n"
  },
